                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d401">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.C1112/85: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Consul at Geneva</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gilbert</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-12-15T17:00:00-05:00"
                            >December 15, 1936—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>160. Your 480, November 24, 5 p.m. and subsequent telegrams concerning raw
                    materials inquiry. We believe this inquiry could serve a useful purpose both in
                    securing further recognition of the necessity of reviving international trade
                    and in subjecting to careful scrutiny certain inadequate ideas concerning
                    economic conditions. We are inclined to favor American participation on the
                    distinct understanding that the Committee is to be one of technical inquiry and
                    that there will be no direct discussion of European political problems. Please
                    confer with Stoppani and cable whether you believe our understanding is fully
                    justified.</p>
                <p>As to the method of participation, we believe that the second or third methods
                    indicated in the Resolution of October 10 offer a wider range of selection.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Moore</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
